                        </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="a3"><desc type="GuestText"><locus target="#ir(ecto)" facs="001"/> The first line of <title type="incomplete" ref="LIT3108RepCh388"/>, and in pencil: beginning (greeting) to a letter</desc></item>
                      <item xml:id="a4"><desc><locus target="#iv(erso)" facs="002"/>, red ink <q>“your servant, Wäldä Mädḫǝn.”</q> </desc></item>
                      <item xml:id="a5"><locus from="143r" to="144r" facs="145"/><desc><title type="complete" ref="LIT3108RepCh388"/>, added by a later hand.</desc></item>
                      <item xml:id="e1"><desc><locus target="#55r" facs="057"/>a small symbol of red and black dots marks the midpoint of the Psalms. This symbol looks very much like a full-stop symbol, except that none of the rest of the full-stop symbols on this folio employ red ink</desc></item>
                      <item xml:id="e2"><desc><locus target="#144v #145r #145v #146r" facs="147 148"/> blank</desc></item>
                      <item xml:id="a6"><desc><locus target="#146v" facs="149"/>in pen: Note about the departure of a wife (divorce or on a trip), in a crude, ink hand</desc></item>
                      <item xml:id="e4"><desc>
                        words of text are written interlinearly, <locus target="#84v #119v" facs="087 122"/>;
                        and lines of text are written interlinearly, <locus target="#23v #123v" facs="026 126"/>;
                        and in the upper margin with a symbol (┴) marking the location where the text is to be
                        inserted, <locus target="#54r" facs="056"> f. 54r, line 17</locus>; <locus target="#132v" facs="135"> f. 132v, col. 2, line 17</locus>; <locus target="#143r" facs="145"> f. 143r, col. 1, line 8)</locus>;
                        text has been removed, e.g., <locus target="#143v" facs="146"/>
                      </desc></item>
                      <item xml:id="e5"><desc>
                        The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line. Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an
                        appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the
                        scribe completes the line of text above or below the end of the line (throughout). This scribe also will reduce the font size at the end
                        of lines to avoid having to go onto the next line, e.g., <locus target="#2v #9v #11r" facs="005 012 013"/></desc></item>
                    </list>
